According to British media, the United States Navy Vice-Minister for Operations, Admiral William Moran, continues to focus on the Asia-Pacific region - the Pentagon - to include the Indian Ocean-Asia-Pacific region - even as the United States Navy is re-energizing its forces to deal with an increasingly worrying Russia on both sides of the Atlantic.
On September 24, the United States website Jane ' s Defence Weekly reported that Russia and China had been listed as strategic competitors in the new United States defence strategy announced earlier in the year.
Since then, the United States Navy has resumed its second fleet in order to confront Russian activities more directly.
Reports suggest that these moves have raised some questions and concerns among allies and analysts about the possibility that the United States Navy might move away from the “Asia-Pacific rebalancing” strategy that marked the Obama Administration.
But Admiral Moran said that the focus of the United States Navy remained on the Western Pacific.
At a round table entitled “Responding to the High Seas Challenge”, organized by the National Asian Research Agency of the United States in Washington on 24 January 2018, he said: “There has been no major change for us. It's not like it's a bad idea.
Moran says: "The focus is still on rebalancing, shifting the weight or whatever you want to describe it. It's not like it's a bad idea.
He acknowledged, however, that the United States had close relations with Europe.
He said, "We will continue to focus on the growth of the West Coast and balance what we can do. It's not like it's a bad idea.
Although Moran points out that the general policy on Russia is within the purview of the US Secretary of Defense, he warns: “The Russians may face demographic and economic challenges, but history has shown that if we clash with them, they will be very tough. It's not like it's a bad idea.
Admiral Moran said that, as part of a renewed US operation against Russia, China, and other competitors, the United States Navy was dynamically deploying its forces into a “new mode of combat,” which would help to surprise the enemy’s air carrier battle groups or other assets at any given time and location.
He said, “We the Navy and the Marines support it — the concept of unpredictability of combat, not to appear in the same place again and again, almost as if it were a stroke — this is what we do. It's not like it's a bad idea.
It was reported that the first attempt at this new approach was by the “Hari Truman” carrier battle group, whose early deployment included working visits to the port and patrolling in areas normally only passing through.
Moran said that the United States Navy was currently working to ensure that allies knew that the ships would remain patrolling in traditional areas and was also addressing logistical and family liaison issues for the new deployment process.
The Royal Australian Navy Commander, Lieutenant General Michael Nunan, also addressed the event, stating that the Australian army could work seamlessly with American carriers.
He said that the situation would continue as the Royal Australian Navy planned to procure nine additional frigates equipped with a Zeus shield operating system.
