China announced a reduction in import duties for 1585 tax purposes, effective 1 November 2018.
Since this year, China has taken successive initiatives to reduce import tariffs.
On 1 May of this year, a total reduction in taxes on medicines was introduced, with zero tariff adjustments for imports for 28 tax purposes, including all generic drugs, including anti-cancer drugs, as well as non-cancer-resistant bio-alkali drugs and actual imports of Chinese medicine.
At the same time, the value added tax on the production and import of anti-cancer drugs has been reduced considerably.
On 1 July, taxes were reduced on cars and spare parts for 218 tax purposes.
With the reduction in taxes, China ' s total car tariff rate is below the average for developing countries and is consistent with the actual Chinese automobile industry.
This reduction will drive industrial restructuring and optimal allocation of resources, accelerate the gains and losses, help to improve the quality of products and services, and is expected to contribute to some extent to the price adjustment of cars and increase consumer benefits.
On 1 July, taxes were reduced on daily consumer goods for 1,449 tax purposes.
The reduction of taxes on daily consumer goods is closely linked to the needs of people for a better life.
The tax reduction was not only significant but also significant, with an average of 56 per cent.
Declining taxes on consumer daily goods directly benefit a wide range of consumers and promote competitiveness in domestic industries.
On 1 November, taxes will be imposed on industrial items such as electrical equipment, spare parts and raw materials for 1585 tax purposes.
The appropriate reduction of tariffs on imports of much-needed industrial goods in some parts of the country can attract more foreign investment, help to increase efficient domestic supply and boost industrial upgrading, and help enterprises to allocate resources globally, reduce production costs and reduce domestic environmental stress.
The head of the office of the Customs and Excise Commission of the Chinese State Council explained that the above-mentioned four autonomous tax reductions, as well as the third step of the reduction, implemented on 1 July this year, in accordance with the outcome of negotiations on the expansion of the information technology agreement, would reduce China ' s overall tariff level from 9.8 per cent in the previous year to 7.5 per cent.
The total level of adjusted tariffs is slightly higher than that of the EU, is lower than that of most developing countries and is at a moderate low level, substantially matching China ' s developing country status and development phase.
The Officer-in-Charge described the overall level of tariffs as one of the important indicators of the openness of China ' s trade in goods, which should be adapted to the stage of China ' s economic development and reflect the characteristics of the times.
