Tariffs are a means of protection for compliance, and tariff levels should be commensurate with industrial competitiveness, encourage good competition and over-protect against industrial development and quality.
The adjustment of tariff rates needs to balance production and consumption needs.
The focus is on lowering commodity tariffs for higher domestic demand and contributing to the upgrading of industries, working to increase imports of niche products with a higher concentration of demand among the population, increasing the awareness of enterprises and the public, and meeting the upgrading needs of industrial and consumer structures.
Tax reductions need to balance fiscal revenues with the affordability of industrial development.
The choice of specific tax-deductible goods and tax-deductive margins needs to be balanced between domestic and foreign markets, upstream and downstream, production and consumption, and to preserve China ' s steady medium-to-medium economic momentum.
The Director-General stressed that this year marks the fortieth anniversary of the reform and opening up of the country, and that China ' s initiative to reduce the overall level of import tariffs is based on China ' s own major initiative to achieve high-quality development needs. It is conducive to the integrated use of both international and foreign resources, the promotion of the quality of domestic supply systems and the satisfaction of the population ' s consumption needs.
This action and initiative demonstrates China ' s firm commitment to a mutually beneficial and win-win open strategy, its firm support for economic globalization, its firm commitment to the principles of free trade and the multilateral trading system, with WTO at its core, and its continued efforts to draw development momentum from its openness to the world and to better benefit China ' s development.
