The Superintendence of Market Supervision recently issued a Circular on Strengthening Market Price Regulation during the National Day of the Mid-Autumn in 2018, which called for the strengthening of price regulation in the area of rental and real estate, the strict regulation of rent price collusion, the accumulation of rental sources, the fabrication of false information to raise rents, the indiscriminate charging of fees by binding services, the publication of misleading price information, the publication of uncoded prices, etc.
The circular made it clear that price monitoring early warning should be enhanced and that market price developments should be closely followed.
There is a need to monitor and analyse price monitoring and early warning by paying close attention to the basic necessities of life, such as food and meat, egg and egg salt, and to changes in the markets and prices of special commodities consumed by the local population during their holidays.
In the event that market volatility is detected, timely and effective measures are taken to address it.
There is a need to strengthen the monitoring and inspection of the wholesale and retail distribution of essential goods, to increase the frequency and regulation of places closely related to the daily consumption of the population, such as supermarkets and agricultural markets, and to ensure that operators operate in good faith and in compliance with the law.
The circular stated that it was necessary to strengthen the inspection of priority areas and create a good consumer environment; to strengthen the regulation of the prices of tickets in state-owned view areas; to focus on violations such as non-compliance with government price levels or floating ranges in state-owned view areas; to increase the price of tickets by means of unauthorized additions to fees; to increase the price of tickets by means of irregular “garden” tickets; to impose high pricing discounts; to bind sales; to de-codify prices; to refrain from implementing preferential measures; to add prices; and to impose surrogate charges.
The notification requirement is to strengthen the regulation of prices of essential goods, especially agricultural products.
In recent times, prices of essential agricultural products, such as vegetables and pork, have fluctuated in some areas, influenced by seasonal variations, natural disasters and outbreaks.
Locally, the market price regulation of agricultural by-products must be strengthened, the production and market supply must be stabilized, and efforts must be made to conduct market-focused and random inspections.
Increased frequency of inspections of commodities such as hard-to-supply and fast-priced pork and serious violations such as hoarding of surprises, price hikes and collusive price hikes.
The circular states that price regulation in the areas of rental housing and real estate needs to be strengthened.
In mid-Autumn, the National Day coincides with the booming season in the sale of housing rentals and goods, with close attention to the price behaviour of real estate enterprises, intermediaries and housing rental-related enterprises, the strict regulation of rent-price collusion, the accumulation of rental sources, the fabrication of false information to raise rents, the indiscriminate charging of fees in the form of tied services, the publication of misleading price information, the issuance of undefined price tags, etc., and the intensification of the inspection of price marks in the sale of hot and selling buildings and housing intermediaries, as well as the detection of non-compliance with the required “one set” to the detriment of consumers and disrupt market order, the purification of the housing market environment and the creation of an open and transparent order of prices in the real estate market.
The circular refers to the effective regulation of prices in other segments of the tourism industry, which is aimed at regulating the price order of restaurants, accommodation, shopping, sightseeing, entertainment, parking, etc., and at directing operators to mark prices, billing and advertising, and seriously investigating and prosecuting all types of price violations.
The circular stated that the inspection of transport prices, such as roads, railways, civil aviation and water transport, should be strengthened and that violations such as price increases, extra-price charges and non-specified prices should be seriously investigated.
Implementation of the “green corridor” for the transportation of fresh agricultural products and exemption from minibus tolls for major holidays.
Innovative regulatory instruments and working methods are needed to increase the dissemination of price laws and regulations for offline and offline retailing enterprises and e-commerce platforms, to urge operators to improve their price promotion programmes and to investigate, in accordance with the law, violations such as fictitious prices, misleading price indications and non-compliance with price commitments.
