On 30 March, journalists learned from the Ministry of Finance that the Ministry of Finance, the National Tax Administration, the National Development and Reform Commission and the Ministry of Commerce had recently issued a joint circular to further encourage foreign investors to invest in China, to allocate profits to foreign investors from enterprises in China, to suspend the application of the income tax policy for domestic direct investment, and to extend the foreign investment incentive scheme to all projects and areas not prohibited from foreign investment.
This policy has been in force since 1 January 2018.
It is clear from the circular that foreign investors ' direct investments on a profit-sharing basis include equity investment by offshore investors on a profit-sharing basis, such as refinancing, new construction and equity acquisitions, but do not include new, additional and acquired shares of listed companies in addition to eligible strategic investments.
If an offshore investor is entitled to a policy of withholding an advance income tax but is not actually entitled to it, he or she may apply for recovery of the policy within three years of the date on which the relevant tax is actually paid and refund the tax paid.
Moreover, foreign investors may continue to benefit from a moratorium on income tax policies if the reorganization of the enterprise into which they are invested meets the requirements of speciality and is actually taxed in accordance with speciality.
In order to ensure that profits from foreign investors are actually used for direct investments, the circular provides that the profits from foreign investors are paid in cash, that the funds are transferred directly from the account of the profit-allocation enterprise to the account of the investing enterprise or equity transferor and may not be made available to other accounts, whether internal or external, prior to direct investment; that the profits from foreign investors for direct investments are paid in non-cash form, such as in-kind, marketable securities, and that the ownership of the assets in question is transferred directly from the profit-allocation enterprise to the enterprise or equity transferor to which the investment is made, and that no other business, person, may hold or temporarily hold the direct investment.
The circular also requires tax authorities to strengthen follow-up regulation in accordance with the law.
If an offshore investor has been granted a moratorium on the imposition of an advance income tax policy and has been certified by the tax authorities as non-conforming by subsequent administration, it is considered that, with the exception of the liability of the profit-allocation company, the foreign investor has failed to declare the enterprise income tax in accordance with the requirements, and will be held liable under the law for the delay in paying the tax, which is calculated from the date the relevant profits are paid.
