On September 29, the Newkyo Radio and Television Department published a Circular on the Special Management of Radio and Television Advertising, which began at the end of this year.
These include advertising for low content, etiquette and low taste, and the broadcasting of health-care birthing programmes on issues that are not documented.
According to the circular, the focus of this special intervention is on nine areas.
These include: advertisements with orientation problems; advertisements with low content, ethos and low tastes; advertisements with excess time and irregular distribution problems; advertisements with exaggerated false propaganda, misleading audiences or programme-form appearances, such as medical, pharmaceutical, medical devices, health-care foods, cosmetics, beauty products, etc.; medical birthing programmes with unrecorded management problems; advertisements with expected return on investment, such as exaggerated false propaganda, misleading audiences, soliciting for fraud, investment funds, collections, etc.; advertisements that induce minors to behave badly or create undesirable values that undermine the physical and mental health of minors; advertisements that do not meet the requirements when public service announcements are broadcast; advertisements that do not meet the requirements; advertisements with inadequate advertising systems, censorship and accountability; and advertisements with other irregularities.
This overhaul will cover all parts of the country, and the requirements of the overhaul and regulation will be fully implemented at all levels of the broadcast media, frequency of channels, programmes and time periods.
The circular requires that all types of illegal advertisements detected in the supervision and inspection of the various branches of the radio and television administration be dealt with in strict conformity with the General Directorate ' s " Procedure for Infringement of Radio and Television Broadcasting Agencies " .
Serious violations are dealt with in a serious manner, such as cautionary statements, the notification of criticism, the suspension of advertising until the frequency channel is suspended, and public exposure to the public, as appropriate.
In recent years, the General Directorate of Radio and Television has repeatedly called for the suspension of illegal advertising.
This year, the National Radio and Television Authority issued a public announcement calling for the suspension of serious irregularities such as “0-buffle milk” and “Sava cocktails” and “Bonritt plant protection from breeding appearances.”
The General Authority for Radio and Television has prepared a number of regulations and circulars regulating the broadcasting of advertisements on radio and television.
The Circular on Further Strengthening the Administration of Television Shopping Advertisements for the Broadcasting of the Veterans Video Channel stipulates that short television Shopping Advertisements may not be broadcast on the VAT channels at 18 to 24 hours a day.
In other times, short television shopping advertisements may not be broadcast by facilitators, or by “selling” exaggerating sound, tone, action, etc., or by “orthopaedic”, “plastic”, “fat” or “slip” propaganda or disguised promotion of breast-rich and fattening products, with no more than one (sub) short television shopping advertisement per hour per day and no more than three minutes each.
The Circular on Further Strengthening the Management of Radio and Television Advertisements provides that television stations must comply strictly with General Directorate ' s Order No. 61 when broadcasting advertisements in the middle of a film show: two commercial advertisements per episode of non-golden time (in 45 minutes) of not more than 1 minute and not more than 30 seconds per episode; one commercial advertisement per concentration of gold time (1990-2100) of not more than one minute; and a reminder of the duration of the advertisement should be given when advertising.
The circular also stipulates that radio and television broadcasters are strictly required to verify the qualifications, certifications, etc. of health-related information advertisements, such as medical, pharmaceutical, medical devices, and health-care foodstuffs, and that the broadcasting of sex-related advertisements is strictly prohibited.
In order to regulate the form of health information advertising, it is not permitted to publish disguised advertisements in the form of health information features.
Health information features should focus on scientific knowledge, such as disease prevention, control and treatment, and should not contain advertising about medicine, medicines, medical devices, health-care foods, and should not be documented on behalf of patients and doctors, pharmacists, specialists, etc.
