Journalists have learned from the National Board of Health that the incidence of malnutrition among our children and young people has decreased compared to decades ago, while the incidence of overweight obesity has increased significantly.
In this regard, experts pointed out that the most important idea of maintaining healthy weight is to “cure undisease” and to promote scientific fitness and proper diet.
According to the Central Information and Interpretation for Adolescent Health Education (2018 edition) recently published by the National Health and Welfare Commission, the key to maintaining healthy weight is rational diet and scientific campaigns.
Overweight, obesity and blind weight loss are not healthy.
The health risks behind the “little chubby” cannot be ignored.
The Director of the Nutrition and Health Unit of the Centre for Disease Prevention and Control in China, Ting Gang, has indicated that obesity is a threat to the normal growth and development of adolescents and has a negative psychological, behavioural, cognitive and intellectual impact. It can even lead to high blood pressure, high blood sugar and high blood resin in children.
At the same time, the vulnerability of adolescents to overweight obesity continues into adulthood, increasing the risk of adolescents becoming adults with chronic diseases such as hypertension and diabetes.
According to Ting Gang, the 2010-2012 nutritional and health testing of Chinese residents showed that our youth aged 6-17 years had a prevalence of 9.6% overweight and 6.4% obese, adding up to 16%.
At the same time, overweight obesity among children and young people is characterized by a higher prevalence of boys than girls and urban than rural areas, with a marked increase in the rate of overweight obesity in recent decades.
How can adolescents cope with overweight obesity?
According to Zhang Zhang, Deputy Director of the Research Centre for Scientific Fitness and Health Promotion of the National Directorate of Sports, obesity among adolescents is currently due mainly to excessive calorie intake and insufficient physical activity.
In the case of simple obesity, emphasis should be placed on scientific sports and reasonable dietary control.
Zhang Zhang pointed out that the most important concept is to maintain healthy weight, the most important of which is to “care for the undisease”, which is to educate schools, parents and students in all aspects of science, to spread awareness of the dangers of overweight and obesity and to raise awareness among adolescents.
Adolescents should undergo periodic medical examinations to monitor growth and development indicators, such as height and weight, and to identify early detection and scientific determination of overweight and obesity, with a view to timely intervention.
For those who are already overweight and obese, the Dinh-Silt Power recommends that, in addition to the active scientific organization of meals and sports, adolescents are at a particular stage of physical development and should refrain from using hunger or semi-hunger therapy to control and reduce body weight and must not be blindly used to reduce weight.
