With the approval of Prime Minister Li Keqiang, the State Council issued the Decision on the Regulation of Licensing for Production of Industrial Products and the Simplified Approval Procedure.
The Decision proposes to further reduce the catalogue of licences for the production of industrial products, eliminate the regulation of licences for the production of 14 categories of industrial products, and devolve authority for the licensing of the production of 4 types of industrial products to the provincial people ' s governments for technical supervision of quality.
As a result of this reform, the implementation of industrial product production licensing will be reduced from 38 last year to the current 24 categories.
The Decision makes it clear that there is a simplified approval process for the catalogue of products.
The first is to replace pre-licensed product inspection by a pre-licensed product inspection by an enterprise submitting, at the time of application, a product inspection report from a qualified testing and inspection agency.
Second, in addition to hazardous chemicals, the technical supervision department of the provincial people ' s government for quality (market supervision) carries out on-site review of the products licensed, and after submitting applications and product inspection qualified reports and making a commitment to ensure product quality security, enterprises receive a production licence after formal clearance and are then subject to on-site review within a specified time frame.
Thirdly, the production of different categories of products in the catalogue of business operations is subject to a review of the issuance of a licence together with a new application for a licence or a renewal of a licence, in accordance with the principle of “one enterprise, one certificate”.
The Decision requires the regions and relevant departments to advance firmly the work on the catalogue and the simplified approval process.
(b) Increase the level of disclosure and back-office review of enterprises ' commitments, strengthen credit monitoring and restraint instruments, enforce corporate responsibility for quality, and revoke production licences in cases of false commitments and non-compliance.
In the case of products that are subject to the elimination of licences for the production of industrial products, there is a need to effectively strengthen post-facto regulation. Products involving public health and safety, environmental protection, etc., can be converted to compulsory certification, positive lists are drawn up and publicized to society, certification standards are harmonized, the costs of compulsory certification are reasonably reduced and certified, and the costs of compulsory certification are, in principle, institutionally covered by all levels of finance.
Support measures to encourage voluntary certification by enterprises and promote branding and market expansion.
The improvement of the quality of industrial products needs to be driven by international standards of excellence.
Full use of third-party social organizations to ensure the quality of industrial products.
In the case of products that retain a licence to manufacture industrial products, the system of standards should be improved, the industry's regulatory advantages should be exploited, the responsibility for “who approves and regulates” should be strengthened, the risks to product quality safety should be assessed on a dynamic basis, and the catalogue should be reduced, approval authority delegated or converted to certification management.
