Reuters, 5 November - The President of Japan’s Central Bank, Haruhiko Kuroda, stated on Monday that the Bank was aware that the long-term imposition of ultra-lax monetary policy could squeeze the profitability of financial institutions and potentially destabilize the country’s banking system.
However, he stated that, given the low inflation and uncertainty in the overseas economies, the JCB needed to maintain its massive stimulus package, while paying close attention to the pros and cons of its policies.
“The Central Bank of Japan fully acknowledges that the strength of financial institutions will be increasingly affected by continued monetary easing.” In an address to business leaders in Nagoya, Haruhiko Kuroda said.
He argued that if financial institutions were to be more proactive in taking on risks to compensate for the shrinking profit margins caused by years of low interest rates, the banking system could become volatile in the event of serious negative shocks.
“Although these risks are not significant at the moment, the central bank will follow the situation closely and encourage financial institutions to take the necessary measures”, he said.
The minutes of the Central Bank of Japan meeting, published earlier Monday, show that at the September conference, the Central Bank of Japan Policy Committee discussed the rising costs of long-term easing.
The minutes of the meeting indicate that one member stated that if the economy continues to expand, “the Bank of Japan will have more policy flexibility in the future. It's not like it's a bad idea.
The minutes of the meeting showed another member that, given the limitations of the duration of the policy, the Committee should discuss how long the Bank of Japan could sustain the stimulus.
Kuroda stated that the Central Bank of Japan would assess the financial risks posed by easing policies, taking into account the uncertainty surrounding Japan ' s economic outlook, which could affect global demand as a result of trade frictions between China and the United States and growing protectionism.
“The impact of such problems on Japan’s economy has been limited for the time being,” said Haruhiko Kuroda.
“However the problem continues, the impact on the Japanese economy may be greater”, he added.
“There is a need to sustain strong monetary easing while considering both positive and negative impacts in a balanced manner,” said Haruhiko Kuroda.
Despite the rise in the ills of radical stimulus packages, such as long-term low interest rates that erode the profits of financial institutions, low inflation forces the Central Bank of Japan to maintain the scheme.
The Central Bank of Japan had maintained monetary policy last month; in the face of the risks posed by the global trade war dispute, Kuroda had ruled out the possibility of rising interest rates in the near future.
