Reuters, September 30, - The CSRC officially released its revised Guidelines on Corporate Governance on Sunday, which focused on further strengthening the constraints on holding shareholders, de facto controllers and their affiliates, focusing more on the protection of small and medium-sized investors, and acting as a protection agency for small and medium-sized investors; and actively drawing on international experience to promote institutional investor involvement in corporate governance.
The SEC noted that the revised guidelines cover the basic concepts and principles of listed corporate governance, the composition and functioning of shareholders ' conferences, boards, supervisory boards, the rights and obligations of directors, supervisors and senior managers, the incentives of listed companies, and the conduct of controlling shareholders and their affiliates.
The new guidelines also include the involvement of institutional investors and related institutions in corporate governance, the basic requirements of listed companies with regard to stakeholders, environmental protection and social responsibility, and information disclosure and transparency.
The revised guidelines require listed companies to implement innovative, coordinated, green, open and shared development concepts in corporate governance, increase party construction requirements for listed companies and strengthen the leading role of listed companies in environmental protection and social responsibility.
Strengthen the Board ' s audit committee role and establish the basic framework for environmental, social responsibility and corporate governance (ESG) information disclosure.
In addition, in response to concerns, the new guidelines put new demands on the stability of control faced by listed corporate governance, the functioning of independent directors, high-level evaluation and incentive restraint mechanisms for directors of listed companies, and enhanced information disclosure.
The CVM also stated that, in accordance with the new guidelines, it would study and refine the relevant regulations and normative documents, and guide self-regulatory organizations such as the stock exchange and the Chinese Association of Listed Companies in developing and revising the relevant rules of self-regulation and gradually improving the system of rules governing listed corporate governance.
At the same time, the training of listed companies has been stepped up, the self-consciousness of listed companies in improving governance and regulating their operations has been strengthened and the quality of listed companies has been continuously improved.
