The Officer-in-Charge indicated that the regulations in force for the implementation of the Personal Income Tax Act provide special advantages for the taxation of persons abroad, and that persons who do not have residence in China but live for a period of more than one year and less than five years may pay personal income tax only in respect of a portion of the income paid by units in China or individuals.
Part of the payments made abroad are not subject to personal income tax in China.
The Ministry of Finance, the State Tax Administration, the State Development and Reform Commission and the Ministry of Commerce of China have also issued circulars expanding the scope of application of the policy of withholding income tax payments from foreign investors for direct investment in the distribution of profits.
The profits allocated to foreign investors from resident enterprises in China for direct investment in China are suspended from the application of the policy of pre-image income tax, and the foreign investment incentive category is extended to all projects and areas not prohibited from foreign investment.
During the 73rd session of the United Nations General Assembly, some positive messages were released on the Korean peninsula.
The President of the Republic of Korea, in his statement, conveyed his country's “irreversible” decision to abandon nuclear weapons and indicated that United States President Trump and North Korean supreme leader Kim Jong-un might meet before the end of the year.
The United States Department of State subsequently stated that Secretary of State Pompeyo would visit the Democratic People ' s Republic of Korea in October to facilitate the implementation of the commitments made at the meeting between United States and Korean leaders in Singapore.
From the beginning of this year to the present, the Democratic People ' s Republic of Korea has broken the ice to open the path of dialogue, and the leaders of the Democratic People ' s Republic of Korea, the Democratic People ' s Republic of Korea and the United States have met. The general trend towards a de-escalation of the situation on the peninsula has continued, as has the principle of dialogue in resolving the problems on the peninsula.
First, the fact that “the issue of the peninsula is essentially a security issue” remains unchanged, and that the key to achieving peace on the peninsula is to address the legitimate security concerns of the parties in a sound and balanced manner, rather than to put pressure on each other and to focus on their claims.
Second, in the dialogue towards the denuclearization of the peninsula, the parties concerned remain divided on the steps and modalities for the denuclearization of the peninsula, and the “who first” game thinking remains strong, owing to the chronic lack of political trust between the DPRK and the United States.
At the Security Council's public meeting on the Korean peninsula, held at United Nations Headquarters in New York, the different voices around the issue of sanctions against the Democratic People's Republic of Korea once again highlighted these two points as “unchanged”.
United States Secretary of State Pompeyo insisted that sanctions against the DPRK would not be lifted until the Korean peninsula was completely denuclearized.
Russian Foreign Minister Lavrov, for his part, stressed the principle of “action in response” by pointing out that “the weakening trend of sanctions should be the same as the steps taken by North Korea on the path to nuclear abandonment.”
There is no doubt that the parties concerned should continue to implement the Council's resolutions in a comprehensive, complete and accurate manner, but that pressure is not an end in itself and that the implementation of sanctions and the promotion of a political settlement are the requirements of the Council's resolutions. The two must not be sidelined.
As Wang Yi, Secretary of State and Minister for Foreign Affairs of China, said, given the current positive developments in inter-Korean, inter-Korean and inter-American relations, China believes that it is necessary for the Security Council to consider launching reversible provisions in due course, thus encouraging the DPRK and all parties concerned to take further steps towards denuclearization.
Looking back, the denuclearization of the peninsula and every progress in the peace process require sufficient political courage from the parties.
At present, in the face of the growing expectations of the international community for a political solution to the issue of the peninsula, it is particularly important for the parties concerned to show political will, make political decisions, implement their commitments, resolve their difficulties and continue to take steps in the direction of one another, advance the process of denuclearization of the peninsula in parallel with the establishment of peace mechanisms on the peninsula and work together to establish a permanent peace on the peninsula.
