Health centres and health posts provide influenza vaccination services especially during the national holiday.
This year, the Health Department ordered 150,000 doses of 4-valent influenza vaccine for 2018-2019, giving priority at this stage to free vaccination for high-risk persons, and providing vaccinations at health centres and health posts under the authority of the Health Department, especially from 9 a.m. to 1 p.m. on the National Day holiday (1 and 2 October).
In addition to the above-mentioned outreach measures, health centres and health posts under the Health Service have, since the launch of the programme, been extended to 8 p.m. on Mondays to Fridays. As of 30 September at 4 p.m., 4,158 people have been vaccinated, up from 3,714 in the same period last year.
Free vaccinations are provided to the following Macao residents: 6 months to 18 years of age, persons aged 50 years and over, pregnant women, all chronically ill persons, including those who are obese (i.e. BMI with a body quality index of 30 or more), as well as institutions, nurseries, kindergartens, primary and secondary schools, all health workers, and Macao residents working in lottery playgrounds.
At the same time, other persons, including the public sector, deemed necessary for vaccinations by the Health Service, will contact the relevant agencies on their own initiative to obtain a list of such vaccinations, which will be arranged by the health centre.
In order to facilitate the vaccination of the inoculations and the reduction of the waiting time of the province, the Health Department will send medical personnel to Hong Kong ' s secondary schools, primary schools, kindergartens and nurseries between October and December this year to provide mass influenza vaccinations for young children, young and middle-school students, teachers and employees; in addition, the Health Department will arrange group vaccinations for the elderly and disabled, public sector or other institutions.
If students and young children fail to participate in group vaccinations, they can be vaccinated from 3 December 2018 on the basis of a Macao resident ' s identity card, a health office user ' s card, a influenza vaccination card, if any, a student ' s certificate, an employee ' s card or a vocational certificate at the general hospital or a health centre.
The Department of Health reminded the population that, between September 2017 and August 2018, people who had been vaccinated against influenza 2017 to 2018 would still need to be vaccinated against the new influenza season in September 2018. The antigens of influenza contained in the influenza vaccine of the northern hemisphere of 2018-2019 were updated in response to seasonal influenza in the northern hemisphere in winter 2018-2019 and summer 2019.
The peak of influenza in Macao is usually in January-March of each year, later than in temperate areas (such as northern China and Japan), and the Health Authority has called for early vaccination of those at high risk who are more vulnerable to complications from influenza, such as the elderly, children, pregnant women, obesity and chronically ill, as well as those who are in constant contact with them.
