Since the mid-2000s, as China ' s demand for oil seeds grew, Paul Thomas, a North Dakota farmer in the United States, grew growing soybeans in his land.
This transition peaked this year, when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans in 5,000 acres, on a scale never seen before.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to replant, by 2019, the staple crops of the former American agricultural zone: maize and wheat.
For the first time in 35 years, United States farmers have grown more soybeans than maize this year.
The planned conversion of other food crops was due to the difficulties faced by United States farmers in selling soybeans in the context of the trade war launched by United States President Trump against China.
China usually buys about 60 per cent of United States exports of soybeans, but in recent months, trade wars have led to almost zero purchases of soybeans, resulting in soybeans prices falling to 10 years of low prices.
Thomas intends to grow more wheat next year, hoping to earn more by reducing dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand.
Thomas says that soybean prices “have hit us hard”.
