In recent years, there have been many instances of school plastic runway irregularities.
To that end, the Ministry of Education has issued a circular requiring the implementation of the new national logo for surface sports sites for synthetic materials for primary and secondary schools to be delivered after 1 November this year.
The mandatory national standard, " Grounds for the fielding of synthetic materials in primary and secondary schools " , which was led by the Ministry of Education and was drafted with the participation of 26 research institutes and testing agencies, was revised over two years by organizing more than 100 expert meetings during which it was validated, as well as country-wide field visits, sample tests and the collection of numerous validation experiments involving hundreds of enterprises in the market.
Journalists have found that the new national marker has not only changed from a “national recommended standard” to a “national mandatory standard” but has also added a number of elements, including thickness requirements, physical performance, age-resilient performance, inorganic filling requirements, high-polymer content requirements for slide-resistant particles, limits on hazardous material for surface-forming products, and limits on hazardous substances for non-solid and solid materials.
In particular, it is worth mentioning that the new national sign limits the amount of hazardous substances that may be produced in the construction of the school plastic runway from the original 7 to 18 items, and regulates the amount of volatile organic matter in the built runway in accordance with the domestic standards.
If the release of hazardous substances is specified in the “Limitation and odour requirements for hazardous substances in ready-made and pre-fabricated surface products”, total volatile organic compounds should not exceed 5 mg/m3, formaldehyde should not exceed 0.4 mg/m3, carbon dioxide should not exceed 7 mg/m3, benzene should not exceed 0.1 mg/m3, and odour levels should not exceed 3 levels.
The new national logo also provides details on sampling requirements for plastic runways at primary and secondary schools, testing rules, sentencing rules, etc.
In addition, for the first time, campus artificial lawns were included in mandatory testing of national standards.
In the near future, special work will be carried out on the implementation of the new national logo, which will be submitted to the Department of Physical Health and Arts Education of the Ministry of Education during the year.
