With effect from 1 November, we reduced some of our most-favoured-nation (MFN) tariff rates to 7.5 per cent.
In accordance with the decision of the State Council at its 26th General Meeting, the State Council Committee on Tariffs and Tariffs issued a bulletin on 30 November 2018 to reduce the most-favoured-nation (MFN) rate for some commodities.
According to the Declaration of the State Council ' s Committee on Tariffs and Tariffs on the Reduction of Tariffs on Imports of Selected Goods, the most-favoured-nation (MFN) rate for certain goods, such as industrial goods, has been reduced as of 1 November this year, in order to meet the demands of industrial upgrading, lower business costs and multi-level public consumption.
There are 1585 tariff lines, which account for about 19% of our total, and the average tax rate has dropped from 10.5% to 7.8%, an average of 26%.
This reduction relates mainly to textiles; stone, ceramic, glass products; parts of iron and steel and base metals; electromechanical equipment and parts such as metalworking machinery, textile machinery, engineering machinery, transmission equipment, electrical appliances, instrumentation instruments, etc.; and resource-based goods and primary processed products such as non-metallic mines, inorganic chemicals, wood and paper products, and precious stones.
At the same time, the tariff rates for imports of imported goods have been adjusted downwards with the overall level of tariffs, particularly on medicines and consumer daily goods.
In order to follow up on the deployment of the Party's central and State Council decisions, we imposed zero tariffs on the vast majority of imported medicines on 1 May of this year, reduced tariffs on imports of cars and parts, some daily consumer goods, and implemented a third-step reduction in the information technology agreement for the extension of products.
Journalists have learned from the State Council’s Committee on Tariffs and Tariffs that, since this year, following successive autonomous adjustments, our overall tariff level has fallen from 9.8% in the previous year to 7.5%, an average reduction of 23%.
Appropriate tariff reductions can contribute to balanced external trade and higher levels of external openness, as well as to the integrated use of both domestic and international resources to advance domestic supply-side structural reforms.
This year, according to the relevant head of the Commission, marks the fortieth anniversary of the reform and opening-up process, and the positive reduction of the overall level of tariffs is a practical step towards implementing the spirit of the important statement made by the Secretary-General Xi at the Boguang Asian Forum, as well as an important step towards the further expansion of openness and the proactive expansion of imports in the light of our own high-quality development needs. This initiative and initiative demonstrate China ' s firm commitment to a mutually beneficial and win-win open strategy, which, while enhancing its own development drive, will also better benefit China ' s development.
