Korea's first joint inspection of Han River into the sea in '65
On the same day, the Korean Ministry of Defence confirmed that the two Koreas had launched a joint expedition into the waters of the open sea of the Han and Jin Rivers.
The initiative is an advance preparation to guarantee the free navigation of civilian vessels on both sides.
The press briefing provided by the Korean Ministry of Defence on the same day indicated that this was the first joint inspection of the Han River entrance since the signing of the Korean War Armistice Agreement in 1953.
In September this year, the two Koreas signed a military agreement to conduct a joint inspection of the waters of the Han River, such as the mouth of the sea, in order to guarantee environmental protection, tourism and so on.
In October, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea planned a joint expedition to the waters at a general-level meeting.
On 5 November, a joint Korean-Korean water expedition was officially launched.
The joint mission consisted of 20 members, including the Korean and Korean military, experts and others.
According to the Korean Ministry of Defence, neither party was armed during the mission and it was prohibited to use the words and actions of the other.
“Because there was no military demarcation line near the entrance to the sea, the area had been an unexpectedly high area, but through joint missions, it would become a new peace zone in the future. It's not like it's a bad idea.
The total length of the waters of this joint Korean-Korean expedition is approximately 70 kilometres, with a total area of approximately 280 square kilometres.
The Ministry of Defence of Korea stated that the Korean side would send six cruise ships to explore, inter alia, the depth of the seawater to provide basic information for safe navigation in the waters and that, after the completion of the survey, navigational maps would be provided for the movement of civilian vessels.
The Democratic People ' s Republic of Korea had held summit talks in Pyongyang in October 2007 to reach an agreement on the joint use of the Han River and the Jinji River at sea, but the follow-up negotiations were stalled by tensions on the peninsula.
According to the military agreement signed by the two Koreas in September, future ships from both sides would need to inform each other in advance before sailing in common waters.
